{"key":"post-17838838","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17838838</id>\n<content>It makes little difference, but I've found agar wedges tend to recover faster laying right on top of the grains rather than shaken in.&amp;nbsp; This also allows contaminants that may have been introduced to show their ugly face if present.&amp;nbsp; Once the mycelium grows off the wedge and into the first layer or two of grains, give it a shake.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When inoculating with spores, don't shake until 20% to 30% colonization, and don't shake again until it's done.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;With grain to grain transfers, you can shake immediately or wait a day or two to shake.&amp;nbsp; It might be a bit faster to wait, but not much.&amp;nbsp; Do whatever is convenient.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17840012</next>\n<prev>17838013</prev>\n<first>17837770</first>\n<last>17840012</last>\n<when>1361423420</when>\n<utime>02/21/13 07:10 AM</utime>\n</post>"}